    "analysis": "From the previous aggregated scan: log.error_count shows many \"anomalies\" across several services (catalogue, front-end, orders, payment, queue-master) because global P95 for log.error_count is 0.0, so any non-zero log count is flagged. Metric-level anomalies are concentrated in the catalogue service (diskio, latency-50, latency-90, mem, workload) with 2 anomaly points each in the incident window and earliest anomalies around 2024-01-19T21:34:00Z. This suggests the catalogue service may have metric degradations starting ~21:34, while logs across many services show errors starting at the same time — possibly indicating a downstream impact or a cascading failure. According to the workflow, we should next perform metric-level fault identification (consecutive anomaly detection) focused on candidate services (catalogue, front-end, orders, payment, queue-master) to determine which component-KPIs have consecutive faults, their start times, durations, and severities. The log.error_count baseline of P95=0 can produce noisy hits, so metrics will help narrow the true root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, for the following candidate components: catalogue, front-end, orders, payment, queue-master, perform per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) analysis:\n1) Compute the global P95 for each full (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series using all available points (do NOT filter by window for P95 calculation).\n2) Filter points to the incident window [2024-01-19 21:31:51 UTC, 2024-01-19 22:01:51 UTC].\n3) For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, count_in_window, count_anomalies_in_window (value >= global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, latest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, max_anomaly_value, mean_anomaly_value, longest_consecutive_anomaly_run_in_window (in minutes).\n4) Limit output to top 20 rows, sort by count_anomalies_in_window desc then by longest_consecutive_anomaly_run_in_window desc. Return compact table only."
}

{
    "analysis": "Metric-only analysis narrowed candidates to catalogue, front-end, orders, payment, and queue-master. Metrics show catalogue has multiple small metric anomalies (cpu, diskio, latencies, mem, workload) with earliest anomalies around 2024-01-19T21:34:00Z. front-end and queue-master show many anomalies but these may be artifacts: front-end/error has global P95 = 0 so every point is flagged; queue-master/socket is constantly at or above P95 (all 25 points). Other services (orders, payment) show minor metric anomalies (2 points each). Logs previously aggregated indicated pervasive log.error_count hits across many services starting ~21:34:00Z, but that summary did not show raw values. To localize the root cause we must verify whether log.error_count represents real non-zero error events and inspect error_log messages for meaningful stacktraces or errors. Next, we should pull raw log.error_count rows (timestamp, value) for the candidate services during the incident window and sample error_logs messages for those services to see concrete error content and earliest error timestamps.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv and error_logs.csv, focus on cmdb_id in [catalogue, front-end, orders, payment, queue-master]:\n1) From log.csv filter rows where log_name == 'log.error_count' and timestamp within [2024-01-19 21:31:51 UTC, 2024-01-19 22:01:51 UTC]. For each cmdb_id return: cmdb_id, count_in_window, sum_error_count (sum of value), earliest_nonzero_error_timestamp_utc (if any), number_of_nonzero_points, and a sample of up to 10 raw rows (timestamp_utc, value) per cmdb_id. Limit the sample output to at most 50 rows total.\n2) From error_logs.csv filter rows for the same cmdb_ids and the same time window. Return: per-cmdb_id counts of error_log messages in window, earliest_error_log_timestamp_utc, and up to 20 sample rows across all these cmdb_ids with columns (timestamp_utc, cmdb_id, message). \nReturn the two compact summaries (log counts/samples and error_log counts/samples)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps: aggregated metrics indicated candidate faulty services: catalogue (multiple metric anomalies across cpu, diskio, mem, latencies, workload with earliest anomalies ~2024-01-19T21:34:00Z), front-end and queue-master showed many flagged anomalies but those appear to be artifacts (front-end error P95=0 and log.error_count values are actually all zeros; queue-master/socket was constantly at P95). log.csv row-level checks showed log.error_count values are all 0.0 for the candidate services during the window and error_logs.csv has no messages — so there are no raw error logs to explain failures. Given multiple service-level metric anomalies and lack of error logs, the next step is trace analysis to find which faulty service is the most downstream faulty component in call chains and to confirm timing. We should analyze trace.csv for the candidate components (catalogue, front-end, orders, payment, queue-master) by computing global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full series (pre-window), then inspecting anomalies in the incident window to get counts, earliest anomaly times and anomaly severities. This will help decide whether catalogue (or another service) is the root cause based on downstream trace position and timing.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv and focusing only on cmdb_id in [catalogue, front-end, orders, payment, queue-master]:\n1) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 using all available points (do NOT filter by the incident window for this calculation).\n2) Then filter rows to the incident window [2024-01-19 21:31:51 UTC, 2024-01-19 22:01:51 UTC].\n3) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) return: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, count_in_window, count_anomalies_in_window (value >= global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (if any), max_anomaly_value_in_window, mean_anomaly_value_in_window.\n4) Limit output to top 20 rows, sorted by count_anomalies_in_window desc, then by max_anomaly_value_in_window desc. Return only this compact table."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps: aggregated metrics pointed to catalogue (multiple metric anomalies around 21:34 UTC) as the most suspicious service. Log analysis showed log.error_count flags were artifacts (all zeros) and error_logs contained no messages. A trace analysis instruction was previously issued but the Executor failed — before computing thresholds and anomalies on traces we must confirm which trace keys exist for the candidate services (per RULE 2.4). Listing available trace_name keys will ensure subsequent trace analysis targets valid fields and avoids another failed execution.",
