    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. For each cmdb_id in [catalogue, front-end, orders, payment, queue-master] compute and return a compact table with: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_rows_in_full_series, earliest_timestamp_utc_in_full_series, latest_timestamp_utc_in_full_series. Limit output to at most 50 rows and sort by cmdb_id then trace_name. Also return a small summary of total trace rows per cmdb_id (cmdb_id, total_trace_rows). Return only these two compact summaries."
}

I reviewed the metric, log, and trace analysis. Metrics show a clear, early, and large deviation in catalogue.diskio starting at ~2024-01-19T21:34:00Z (disk IO max ≈ 67721.71 vs global P95 ≈ 30010.51, >2× baseline). Application logs contain no errors and trace data for these services is absent, so the strongest, earliest, and most significant signal is catalogue disk I/O saturation. Therefore the root cause is the catalogue service experiencing high disk I/O usage.

